{{Infobox power station | name = Fangchenggang Nuclear Power Plant | image = | image_caption = | location_map = China | coordinates = {{coord|21|40|15|N|108|33|30|E|region:CN-35_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | country = People's Republic of China | location = Hongsha, [[Gangkou District|Gangkou]], [[Fangchenggang]], [[Guangxi]] | operator = [[Guangxi Fangchenggang Nuclear Power Group]] | construction_began = 30 July 2010 | commissioned = 1 January 2016 | decommissioned = | status = O | np_reactor_supplier = | np_reactor_type = [[CPR-1000]], [[CPR-1000#Hualong_One_merged_design|HPR-1000]] | np_cooling_source = [[Gulf of Tonkin]] | np_cooling_towers = no | ps_units_operational = 2 × 1000 MW | ps_units_decommissioned = | ps_units_uc = 2 × 1000&nbsp;MW | ps_units_planned = 2 × 1000&nbsp;MW | ps_electrical_capacity = <!-- sum of gross reactor power [MW]-->2,000 | cost = | website = }}
'''Fangchenggang Nuclear Power Plant''' is a [[nuclear power plant]] under construction in [[Fangchenggang]], near Hongshacun Village ( 红沙村 ),<ref name=sino-us>{{cite news |url= http://www.sino-us.com/68/Chinas-Fangchenggang-natural-beauty-and-port-economy.html |title= China’s Fangchenggang: natural beauty and port economy |publisher=Sino-US.com |date=9 June 2013 |accessdate=6 February 2016}}</ref> autonomous region of [[Guangxi]] ([[Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region]]) in the [[People's Republic of China]]. A total of six reactors are planned to operate at the Fangchenggang site. Units 1 and 2 are both [[CPR-1000]]s, units 3–6 are planned to be based on [[Hualong One]] reactors. Fangchenggang 3 and 4 will be the reference plant for the proposed Bradwell B plant in the UK.<ref name=wnn-20151231>{{cite news |url= http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/C-Chinese-firms-join-forces-to-market-Hualong-One-abroad-31121502.html |title=Chinese firms join forces to market Hualong One abroad |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=31 December 2015 |accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref>
The plant is located about 45 kilometres from the border with [[Vietnam]]. It is a project of Guangxi Fangchenggang Nuclear Power Group, a joint venture between China Guangdong Nuclear Power Co (CGNPC) and Guangxi Investment Group.<ref name=wnn-20100803>{{cite news |url= http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-Construction_of_Fangchenggang_plant_starts-0308104.html |title=Construction of Fangchenggang plant starts |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=3 August 2010 |accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref>
Unit 1 was connected to the electricity grid on 25 October 2015.<ref name=wnn-2610154>{{cite news |url= http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-First-Fangchenggang-unit-connected-to-grid-2610154.html |title=First Fangchenggang unit connected to grid |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=26 October 2015 |accessdate=6 February 2016}}</ref> Unit 1 is commercially operating starting on 1 January 2016. <ref name=iaea-943>{{cite news |url= https://www.iaea.org/PRIS/CountryStatistics/ReactorDetails.aspx?current=943 |title= FANGCHENGGANG-1 Operational Details |publisher=International Atomic Energy Agency |date=1 January 2016 |accessdate=6 February 2016}}</ref>
Construction works for Unit 3 started in December 2015.<ref name=pt-fnpp>{{cite news |url= http://www.power-technology.com/projects/fangchenggang-nuclear-power-plant-guangxi/ |title= Fangchenggang Nuclear Power Plant, Guangxi, China |publisher=Kable Intelligence Limited |date= |accessdate=6 February 2016}}</ref> Unit 3 first concrete pour occurred on 24 December 2015.<ref name=chnpc-209063>{{cite news |url= http://en.cgnpc.com.cn/n1017152/n1017227/c1209063/content.html |title= CGN’s Fangchenggang-3 begins construction with first concrete pour |publisher= China General Nuclear Power Corporation |date= 24 December 2015 |accessdate= 6 February 2016 |deadurl= yes |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160206133225/http://en.cgnpc.com.cn/n1017152/n1017227/c1209063/content.html |archivedate= 6 February 2016 |df= }}</ref> First concrete for Unit 4 followed one year later, on 23 December 2016.<ref name=wnn-29121601>{{cite news |url= http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-Construction-starts-on-second-Hualong-One-29121601.html |title=Construction starts on second Hualong One |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=29 December 2016 |accessdate=8 January 2017}}</ref>
