{{Generalize|date=October 2009}}
'''[[Density|Radiation]] flux''' is a measure of the amount of [[Particle radiation|radiation]] received by an [[Physical body|object]] from a given source. This can be any type of radiation, including [[Electromagnetic radiation|electromagnetic]], [[sound]], and particles from a [[radioactive]] source.

Φ = {{frac|L|4&pi;r<sup>2</sup>}} is the radiation flux, L is the [[luminosity]], or total power output of the source, and r is the distance from the radiation source. The units of radiation flux are W·m<sup>−2</sup>, or kg·s<sup>−3</sup>.

Radiation flux [[density]] is a related measure that takes into account the area the radiation flux passes through, and is defined as the [[flux]] divided by the area it passes through. The Radiation flux density is also known as [[Intensity (physics)|Intensity]] where I = {{frac|L|4πr<sup>2</sup>}}

