{{Infobox book | name = To See Every Bird on Earth | title_orig = | translator = | image = To See Every Bird on Earth.jpg | caption = | author = Dan Koeppel | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = | series = | subject = [[Birdwatching]] | genre = | publisher = [[Penguin Group|Hudson Street Press-Penguin Group]] | release_date = 2005 | english_release_date = | media_type = | pages = 304 | isbn = 1-59463-001-1 | dewey= 598/.072/34 22 | congress= QL677.5 .K614 2005 | oclc= 57414552 | followed_by = [[Banana: The Fate of the Fruit That Changed the World]] }}
'''''To See Every Bird on Earth: A Father, a Son, and a Lifetime Obsession''''' is a book by [[Dan Koeppel]] first published in 2005. It is about the author's relationship with his father Richard Koeppel, an obsessive "Big Lister" [[birdwatchers|birdwatcher]] who had spotted over 7000 different species of birds at the time the book was written. The book focuses on Dan Koeppel's attempts to understand the obsession that ruled his father's life. It also examines the culture on highly competitive birders who travel the world making lists of their sightings, and discusses the history and rules of listing. Richard Koeppel was diagnosed with cancer in 2000, which curtailed his birding and forced him to switch to butterflies found locally near his home on Long Island, New York. He [http://www.easthamptonstar.com/?q=Obituaries%2F2012815%2FRichard-J-Koeppel died] of cancer-related causes on August 2, 2012.
